{{Other people|William Lilly}} {{EngvarB|date=November 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}} {{Infobox writer | name = W. S. Lilly | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birth_name = William Samuel Lilly | birth_date = {{Birth date|df=y|1840|7|10}} | birth_place = [[Dorset]], England | death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|1919|8|29|1840|7|10}} | death_place = [[West Kensington]], London | occupation = Historian, [[jurist]] | nationality = English | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | notable_works = | spouse = Anna Marie Lilly | children = | relatives = | influences = | influenced = | signature = }} '''William Samuel Lilly''' (10 July 1840 – 29 August 1919)<ref>"Death of Mr. W.S. Lilly," ''The Times,'' 1 September 1919, p. 13.</ref> was an English [[barrister]] and man of letters.
==Biography== Lilly was born at Fifehead, [[Dorset]], in 1840. He was educated at [[Peterhouse, Cambridge]], taking his degree of [[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]] in 1862, and his [[Master of Laws|LL.M.]] in 1870. After some private tuition from Sir [[Adolphus William Ward]], he entered the Indian civil service, becoming in 1869 secretary to the government of [[Chennai|Madras]]. Owing to a breakdown in health, however, he had to return to England, where he devoted himself to a career in literature. With his wide-ranging intellectual interests, Lilly occasionally wrote for some of the major publications of his time, such as [[The Nineteenth Century (periodical)|''The Nineteenth Century,'']] ''[[The Contemporary Review]],'' ''[[The Fortnightly Review]]'', [[Popular Science|''Popular Science Monthly,'']] and [[Dublin Review (Catholic periodical)|''The Dublin Review'']].
Lilly was a convert to [[Roman Catholicism]], and from 1874 was secretary to the Catholic Union of Great Britain. He was also a Justice of the Peace for [[Middlesex]] and London.
